hints_latex:
Recall that the general form of a (left) Riemann sum is

\begin{align*}
\int_a^b f(y)\,dy = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \sum_{j=0}^{n-1} \Delta y\,f(y_j),
\end{align*}

where $y_j = a + j\Delta y$ and $\Delta y = \frac{b-a}{n}$.

sols_latex:
We can recognize this as the limit of a Riemann sum. Let's first put
this into summation notation:

\begin{align*}
f(x) = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \sum_{j=0}^{n-1} \frac{1}{2 + (1+j(x-1)/n)^3} \cdot \frac{x-1}{n}
\end{align*}

Note that when $j=0$ this gives us the 1/3 term in the sum. We put the
factor $(x-1)/n$ first to resemble the general form of a (left) Riemann
sum as given in Hint 3.

Ultimately, we aim to express $f(x)$ as a definite integral i.e.
something of the form

\begin{align*}
\int_a^b g(s) ds = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \sum_{j=0}^{n-1}  g(s_j) \cdot \Delta s
\end{align*}
We choose $s$ here for ease of notation and not overuse the $x$ symbol.

For $x$ fixed, we can read off an interval spacing of

\begin{align*}
\Delta s = \frac{x-1}{n}
\end{align*} Let's rewrite the sum with $\Delta s$ in
place of $(x-1)/n$:

\begin{align*}
f(x) = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \sum_{j=0}^{n-1} \frac{1}{2+(1+j \Delta s)^3} \cdot \Delta s.
\end{align*}

This is suggestive of a left-endpoint Riemann sum, since we start with
$j=0$ and end at $j=n-1$. In that case, we can take our subinterval
endpoints to be $s_j = 1+ j \Delta s$ (recall that when we do a Riemann
sum, we have subintervals with endpoints that look like
$s_j = a + j \Delta s$ and terms of the form $1 + j \Delta s$ are of
this form).

Let's rewrite this as

\begin{align*}
f(x) = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \sum_{j=0}^{n-1} \frac{1}{2 + s_j^3} \cdot \Delta s
\end{align*}

From here, we read off

\begin{align*}
g(s) = \frac{1}{2+s^3}
\end{align*}

Also, since $s_0 = 1 + 0 \Delta s = 1$ is the lower bound and
$s_n = 1 + n \Delta s = 1 + n (x-1)/n = x$ is the upper bound, our final
result is that

\begin{align*}
f(x) = \int_1^x \frac{1}{2+s^3} ds
\end{align*}

Finally we can compute the equation of the tangent line to $f(x)$ at
$x=1$. All we need are $f(1)$ and $f'(1)$.

\begin{align*}
f(1) = \int_1^1 g(s) ds = 0
\end{align*} since we are integrating over a range of
zero.

And by the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus,

\begin{align*}
f'(x) = \frac{1}{2+x^3}
\end{align*} so

\begin{align*}
f'(1) = \frac{1}{3}
\end{align*}

Hence the equation of the tangent line is

\begin{align*}
y-0 = \frac{1}{3}(x-1)
\end{align*} or simply

\begin{align*}
y = \frac{1}{3} (x-1)
\end{align*}

statement_latex:
Let

\begin{align*}
f(x) = \lim_{n \to \infty} \left[ \left\{ \frac{1}{3} + \frac{1}{2+\left( 1+\frac{x-1}{n} \right)^3} + \frac{1}{2+\left( 1+\frac{2(x-1)}{n} \right)^3} + \ldots \right.\right.
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
\ldots + \left.\left.\frac{1}{2+\left( 1+\frac{(n-1)(x-1)}{n} \right)^3} \right\} \frac{x-1}{n} \right]
\end{align*}
where \emph{x} $\geq$ 0. Find the equation of the tangent line to the
graph \emph{y} = \emph{f}(\emph{x}) at \emph{x} = 1.
